│ identified the instruction `I` that causes the assertion failure:\n\n```llvm\n%iv.1.lcssa2 │
│ = phi i64 [ %iv.1, %loop.1 ]\n```\n\nThis is a new PHI node created by the `SCEVExpander`. │
│ Its user is:\n\n```llvm\n%4 = trunc i64 %iv.1.lcssa2 to i32\n```\n\nThe `trunc`            │
│ instruction (`%4`) is *not* in the `InsertedSet` of the `SCEVExpanderCleaner`, hence the   │
│ assertion failure. The `trunc` is part of the logic being built by the Loop Vectorizer,    │
│ which needs the value of `%iv.1` to proceed.\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\n1.  The Loop │
│ Vectorizer analyzes `loop.2` and needs to determine its trip count. ScalarEvolution        │
│ identifies the trip count as being related to the value of `%iv.1`.\n2.  From the          │
│ perspective of `loop.2`, `%iv.1` is a `SCEVUnknown`. To get a concrete `Value*` for it at  │
│ the correct program point (the preheader of `loop.2`), the `SCEVExpander` must determine   │
│ the value of `%iv.1` after `loop.1` exits.\n3.  The expander calls                         │
│ `getPHIValueAfterLoop()` to handle this. This function correctly deduces the exit value of │
│ the PHI. To materialize this value in the IR, it needs to expand the corresponding SCEV    │
│ expression.\n4.  Here lies the error: `getPHIValueAfterLoop` uses the *current*            │
│ `SCEVExpander` instance (the one owned by `GeneratedRTChecks`) to expand the expression.   │
│ This causes the newly created instruction (`%iv.1.lcssa2`) to be registered in the         │
│ `Inserted` list of the `SCEVExpanderCleaner`.\n5.  The Loop Vectorizer then takes this new │
│ instruction and uses it to build further IR for the vectorized loop (the `trunc`           │
│ instruction).\n6.  When the `GeneratedRTChecks` object goes out of scope, its cleaner      │
│ tries to delete all instructions it created, including `%iv.1.lcssa2`. It discovers the    │
│ `trunc` user, which it doesn't own, and correctly asserts.\n\nThe fundamental problem is   │
│ that `getPHIValueAfterLoop` is creating an instruction that is intended to be a persistent │
│ result for the caller (the Loop Vectorizer), but it's being created by a temporary         │
│ expander that will try to clean it up.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix is to   │
│ ensure that when `getPHIValueAfterLoop` generates an instruction, that instruction is not  │
│ registered for cleanup by the current expander. The cleanest way to do this is to create a │
│ new, temporary, \"dirty\" (non-cleaning) `SCEVExpander` instance for the sole purpose of   │
│ generating this one instruction.\n\nThe relevant code is at the end of                     │
│ `SCEVExpander::getPHIValueAfterLoop`:\n\n```cpp\n//                                        │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/ScalarEvolutionExpander.cpp:1888\n  return expandCodeFor(Final,  │
│ Ty, L->getExitBlock()->getTerminator());\n```\n\nThis line uses the `this` expander. It    │
│ should be changed to use a new, local expander:\n\n```cpp\n// Proposed Change\n            │
│ SCEVExpander Exp(*SE, DL, IVName.c_str());\n  return Exp.expandCodeFor(Final, Ty,          │
│ L->getExitBlock()->getTerminator());\n```\n\nThis creates a new expander `Exp` on the      │
│ stack. Since it's not associated with a `SCEVExpanderCleaner`, any instructions it creates │
│ will persist in the function, which is the desired behavior. The instruction becomes a     │
│ normal part of the IR for the Loop Vectorizer to use.\n\n### 5. Conclusion\n\nBy creating  │
│ and using a local, non-cleaning `SCEVExpander` inside `getPHIValueAfterLoop`, we decouple  │
│ the generation of the PHI's exit value from the cleanup mechanism of the calling expander. │
│ This allows the generated instruction to persist and be used by subsequent                 │
│ transformations, fixing the assertion failure."})                                          │
