│ for the vectorized loop (the `trunc` instruction).                                         │
│ 6.  When the `GeneratedRTChecks` object goes out of scope, its cleaner tries to delete all │
│ instructions it created, including `%iv.1.lcssa2`. It discovers the `trunc` user, which it │
│ doesn't own, and correctly asserts.                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fundamental problem is that `getPHIValueAfterLoop` is creating an instruction that is  │
│ intended to be a persistent result for the caller (the Loop Vectorizer), but it's being    │
│ created by a temporary expander that will try to clean it up.                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to ensure that when `getPHIValueAfterLoop` generates an instruction, that       │
│ instruction is not registered for cleanup by the current expander. The cleanest way to do  │
│ this is to create a new, temporary, "dirty" (non-cleaning) `SCEVExpander` instance for the │
│ sole purpose of generating this one instruction.                                           │
│                                                                                            │
│ The relevant code is at the end of `SCEVExpander::getPHIValueAfterLoop`:                   │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```cpp                                                                                     │
│ // llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/ScalarEvolutionExpander.cpp:1888                              │
│   return expandCodeFor(Final, Ty, L->getExitBlock()->getTerminator());                     │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ This line uses the `this` expander. It should be changed to use a new, local expander:     │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```cpp                                                                                     │
│ // Proposed Change                                                                         │
│   SCEVExpander Exp(*SE, DL, IVName.c_str());                                               │
│   return Exp.expandCodeFor(Final, Ty, L->getExitBlock()->getTerminator());                 │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ This creates a new expander `Exp` on the stack. Since it's not associated with a           │
│ `SCEVExpanderCleaner`, any instructions it creates will persist in the function, which is  │
│ the desired behavior. The instruction becomes a normal part of the IR for the Loop         │
│ Vectorizer to use.                                                                         │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 5. Conclusion                                                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ By creating and using a local, non-cleaning `SCEVExpander` inside `getPHIValueAfterLoop`,  │
│ we decouple the generation of the PHI's exit value from the cleanup mechanism of the       │
│ calling expander. This allows the generated instruction to persist and be used by          │
│ subsequent transformations, fixing the assertion failure.                                  │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                                            │
